# Solution

- This one is fun, but I went down a rabbit hole, unfortunately, with ChatGPT. I saw the intermingling of decimal and binary values. So I was more focused on the decimal and figured the 1’s and 0’s were on/offs or maybe decimal + binary and you had to do some shenanigans. Well, that would be wrong. The answer didn’t lie in the decimal values, but the binary values. I had thought about looking at what is going into which register, but ChatGPT is stupid. So I looked through the packet with my trusty filter and found the 1’s and 0’s were being written solely to Register 0 instead of the other random order of registers. What also threw me off was the client => server, server => client duplication of the register values, so we had to handle that.

- Here’s the simplified answer/approach:

```
Wireshark Filter: 

modbus && ip.src == 172.20.10.2 && modbus.func_code == 6 && modbus.regnum16 == 0
```

We use tshark since I was on Windows for this challenge:

```
tshark -r bussing_around.pcapng -Y "modbus && ip.src == 172.20.10.2 && modbus.func_code == 6 && modbus.regnum16 == 0" -T fields -e modbus.regval_uint16 > out.txt
```

- Upload the out.txt or copy the text and throw it in CyberChef. 

![Zip Header](/huntress_2025/Day_18/Bussing_Around/Zip_Header.png "Zip Header")

We see a zip file with the password right there for us. I forgot you could just unzip with a password in [CyberChef](https://gchq.github.io/CyberChef/#recipe=From_Binary('Space',8)Unzip('5939f3ec9d820f23df20948af09a5682',false)&&ieol=CRLF), so I wasted a couple of seconds there. So you just unzip the file with the password and you get the flag!

![CyberChef - Flag](/huntress_2025/Day_18/Bussing_Around/CyberChef.png "CyberChef Flag")
